    4.1 Introduction

    In week 3, we examined mise-en-scène as one aspect of film style. This week we continue our examination of style, shifting our attention to cinematography. As previously noted, cinematography should always be considered in relation to the other aspects of style (mise-en-scène, editing and sound) – all aspects come into play when we view a film.

    What is cinematography? In their book Film Art, Bordwell, Thompson and Smith define cinematography as ‘writing in movement’ (p. 159). The word ‘cinema’ is derived from the ancient Greek word for movement, while the suffix ‘graph’ means ‘written’. Cinematography is all of the techniques employed by the film for writing with light. These include the photographic elements of shot, tonality, exposure and speed of motion, perspective, lens, focal length, as well as lighting, camera position, and framing. Generally speaking, cinematography is concerned with the look of a film through directorial decisions made about how to shoot a scene (e.g. static or mobile framing), the type of photographic technique employed (e.g. wide angled lens, long shot, deep focus etc.), the choice of film stock (fast, slow), the placement of staged lighting (key light, fill light etc.) and other associated techniques. As Giannetti has stated in the set reading for this week, ‘virtually all cinematographers agree that the style of the photography should be geared to the story, theme, and mood of the film’ (p. 37).

    4.2 Realism versus formalism

    Before we begin our consideration of the technical aspects of cinematography, we will first re-examine issues concerning realism in film. In the set reading for this week (a chapter from Understanding Movies by Louis Giannetti), the author begins with a sliding scale of film style, ranging between realism and formalism, with classicism in the centre. If you recall, we have already come across these terms in Week 2. Films can be positioned along the scale between verisimilitude (conventional realism) where the aim of the film is to present a story world as close as possible to what counts for the audience as ‘real life’, and formalism where the aim is to present a story world with its own set of rules for constructing reality.[1] Giannetti suggests that in accordance with this scale, ‘formalist movies have a high degree of manipulation, and stylization of reality’ (p. 3). While we agree with him on this point, we want to add that all films – those tending towards verisimilitude (conventional realism) and those to formalism – are subject to a process of manipulation and shaping. If you recall, in Week 2 we considered the issue of realism in terms of verisimilitude as ‘a particular culture’s coded expectations about artistic representation of reality’ (Pearson, p. 28). Realism is a style based on a verisimilar code for what counts as reality for audiences at any given period of time.

    A good example of how realism is presented in a highly stylised film is Raging Bull (Scorsese 1980). As Giannetti suggests,

    people often praise the ‘realism’ of the boxing matches in Raging Bull. What they really mean is that these scenes are powerful, intense and vivid. These traits owe very little to realism as a style [by this he means that what people are praising is not the realism but its stylisation]. In fact, the boxing matches are extremely stylised. The images are often photographed in dreamy slow motion, with lyrical crane shots, weird accompanying sound effect (like hissing sounds and jungle screams), staccato editing in both images and the sound, and so forth. (pp. 7-8)

    Despite its real life content, Raging Bull employs formalist cinematography and editing in order to produce certain reality effects. So, it is important that we think of realism as a style and not as a self-evident representation of real life. All films are stylized and manipulated. That is, all films are shaped into particular forms through stylizations. Our task this week is to examine how cinematography contributes to this stylized shaping of a film.

    4.3 Framing the scene: the shot

    In Week 3 we considered the issue of framing. We noted that mise-en-scène is always framed by the camera as the bounded space of the screen (Giannetti, p. 42). This week we consider framing from the perspective of the camera as a framing device. The basic unit of the camera is the shot – a single ‘take’ by the camera of whatever is in front of it, recorded either in analogue or digital format. When replayed, shots become visual appearances (images) projected onto a screen (either by a projector, or a video device). Shots can be either short or long in duration or anything in between; they can be taken from a static or moving position; they can be taken using various lenses for certain effects. The format used to record whatever is in front of the camera plays an important part in how the image will look on the screen.

    4.4 Types of shots

    In your reading for this week, the author sets out the types of shots used in film making. There are six categories of shot:

    1. Extreme long shot
    2. Long shot
    3. Full shot
    4. Close up
    5. Extreme close up
    6. Deep focus

    Please read through the description of these shots, familiarising yourself with them. Gain skill in identifying the type of shot in a sequence of any film (you will be asked to identify types of shots in your assignments). If you go to the Power Point presentation for this week you will see a series of screen shots taken from Citizen Kane (one of the recommended films for this week). The first four shots are taken from a sequence which we have named ‘Interview with Bernstein’. See also the sequence of shots taken from Casablanca (the other recommended film), illustrating various types of shots and how they relate to the scene and the film as a whole.

    Exercise

    Examine the sequence of Rear Window where Jeff is speaking to his boss on the telephone (begins about four minutes into the film and lasts about two minutes). Note what types of shot are employed. Can you detect the use of any one type more than others? Why do you think these shots have been employed? Could the sequence be filmed using different types of shot?

    For a good example of the use of deep focus imagery, view Citizen Kane. Welles uses deep focus in a number of scenes. See Power Point presentation.

    4.5 Angles

    The angle of the shot (high, low, eye level, etc.) is determined by the placement of the camera with respect to the object(s) in front of it. The shot’s angle can dictate the type of relation that the viewer has with what is seen, for instance a low angle shot can signify subservience or ‘looking up’ to emphasise a character’s importance. Alternatively, a high angle shot can signify ‘looking down’ which lessens a character’s importance, or provides omniscience or omnipotence over what is seen. In Week 3, section 3.2, we looked at a shot from a sequence in Imitation of Life, ‘Coming Home’ – a low angle shot of two women in conversation. The shot presents the two women in a widening-upward view that emphasises space and proportion, contributing to the overall sense of massiveness of the home and its surrounding terrain.

    Exercise

    Re-examine the telephone sequence in Rear Window, this time in terms of the shot angles. Given what the conversation is about (Jeff’s boss is trying to get him to come back to work), what attitude to do you think that the angle of the shot on Jeff indicates?

    4.6 Lighting

    The source of lighting in a scene can be either diegetic or extra-diegetic. Diegesis means story telling – the way a story is told (Cohan and Shires, p. 88). If something is diegetic it is part of the story, whereas if it is extra-diegetic it is something added to the story, not part of it. For instance, in the penultimate scene of Rear Window where Thorwald attacks Jeff, the blinding light of the flashbulb Jeff uses to defend himself is diegetic – an actual part of the story – whereas the light that illuminates Jeff as he wheels himself around in the darkened room is extra-diegetic – its source is an out- of-frame overhead light that swivels with his movement.

    The three point lighting system

    The three point lighting system is a fundamental part of the classical Hollywood system of film production. It consists of a key light, fill light, and back light. The aim of this system is to allow the director to take control of the light thrown on a subject within a studio setting.

    Figure 1: Three point lighting system

    Key lighting

    The use of low key lighting (subdued) darkens the tone of the film to produce a mood of menace, fear, conspiracy, melancholy or danger, seen for instance in film noir or expressionist films (see the shots of Casablanca in the Power Point presentation); the use of high key lighting (bright, illuminating) accentuates a mood of happiness and optimism, or alternatively high drama, seen in musical, epics and dramatic films.

    For a good description of the key lighting system, see Janey Place and Lowell Peterson, ‘Some Visual Motifs of Film Noir’, one of the set readings for Week 7.

    Figure 2 ‘A candlelit dinner’ Rear Window

    Exercise

    Can you determine the position of the key and fill lights in the shot in Figure 2, occurring about 25 minutes into the film?

    4.7 Colour

    It has to be remembered that colour film was not always the standard format for feature films. From the early days of film (1900s) to the 1950s, colour was the exception rather than the norm. Giannetti provides a clear summary of the basic issues concerning the look of colour film. We can define colour in film using Giannetti’s scale of film style between realism and formalism. Pale, subtle colours with complex patterning tend toward the realist end of the scale, while vivid, monolithic colours tend towards the formalist end. Keep in mind that these are not hard-and-fast rules, but tendencies that change over time according to changes in cultural coding and expectations. Directors often develop their own colour styles, for instance Douglas Sirk’s use of pale colours in some scenes of Imitation of Life (Week 3) is not to signify naturalness but femininity.

    Colour can also be used symbolically to signify certain meanings, for example, red to signify sexual desire or anger, blue to signify peace. Douglas Sirk’s films are well known for their use of excessive colour to undermine the conventions of Hollywood melodrama (see Week 3). In reference to his film Written on the Wind (1956), a film renowned for its use of excessive colour, Sirk comments:

    Almost throughout the picture I use deep-focus lenses which have the effect of giving a harshness to the objects and a kind of enamelled, hard surface to the colours. I wanted this to bring out the inner violence, the energy of the characters which is all inside them and can’t break through. (qtd. in Elsaesser, p. 43)

    Here Sirk indicates how colour can be used for expressive purposes, to suggest repressed violence that saturates an otherwise classically presented story of dynastic greed. The colour of objects can also be used to suggest certain ideas or to act emblematically as signifiers of a certain character or situation. In Rear Window, Hitchcock uses the colour brown to emphasise the oppressive heat of a New York summer. The Power Point presentation shows how colour can be carried from the outside to the inside through the colour of a character’s clothing (see Rear Window shots in Power Point presentation).

    Exercise

    Can you detect any other significant use of colour in Rear Window?

    Filters can be used to provide certain effects, for instance a blue filter can be placed over the lens of the camera to create a ‘day for night’ effect (used to economise by filming night time sequences during the day (B grade Westerns of the 1930s are a good example of day for night shooting). Filters can also be used to colour certain scenes to emphasise seasonal effects (Giannetti, p. 33), or to cast a mood over the story world.

    Exposure: under-exposure creates a shadowy effect, used in film noir and mystery films, while over-exposure creates stark expressive effects.

    Film stock comes in a range of speeds ranging from fast to slow: fast stock is highly sensitive to light, while slow stock is less sensitive to light. Choice of film stock determines how much colour is held in the shot. Slow stock will hold more colour than fast stock. Fast stock is used to produce a documentary effect (graininess).

    Tonal contrast: one of the most common mistakes made about film is that black-and-white films are films that lack colour, as if this were an insurmountable deficit to their aesthetic complexity. This attitude does an injustice to black-and-white films and overlooks tonal contrast as an important feature of film aesthetics. A term commonly used to describe tonal contrast is chiaroscuro (light and shadow). Chiaroscuro is usually applied to the art of sixteenth century Baroque and seventeenth century Dutch painting (e.g. Caravaggio, Rembrandt), but can also be used to describe the lyrical style of black and white and colour films. A film’s chiaroscuro is the way it produces tonal contrast between light and shade. Many of the images in Orson Welles’ Citizen Kane are examples of cinematic chiaroscuro. Hitchcock uses tonal contrast in some of the scenes in Jeff’s apartment in Rear Window. Please refer to the Power Point presentation for examples.

    Exercise

    In Michel Curtiz’s Casablanca, the visual contrast between black and white is used to code the difference between the ‘oscillating forces at play between the characters’ (Deutelbaum 1990, p. 45). Read through Marshall Deutelbaum’s article on visual design in Casablanca. Consider the use of tonal contrast in figure/ground relations in the scenes described by the author.

    4.8 Lenses

    Giannetti sets out the basic types of lenses used in film making (pp. 27-32):

    • Standard range
    • Telephoto
    • Wide angle

    Please read through the set reading and familiarise yourself with these types of lenses and what the can do.

    In Rear Window, about 40 minutes into the film, we see Jeff looking through his binoculars into Thorwald’s apartment. Dissatisfied with the limitations of the view, Jeff decides to exchange the binoculars with the more powerful telephoto lens of his camera. He then looks through the camera where he is now able to see right into Thorwald’s apartment (see Power Point presentation). Note that the outside balcony has now become blurred. As Giannetti explains, ‘most long lenses are in sharp focus on one distance plane only. Objects placed before or beyond that distance blur, go out of focus …’ (p. 27). The telephoto lens[2] picks out the detail of Thorwald wiping the blade of a knife in his kitchen, while blurring detail in the foreground. The effect of this sharp focus on a distant object is to present the illusion of having entered Thorwald’s apartment. Such immersive effects can be seen throughout the film as Jeff’s surveillance of the apartments becomes increasingly intense.

    4.9 Mobile Framing

    In simple terms, mobile framing refers to the movement of the camera. Bordwell, Thompson and Smith describe mobile framing as ‘allow[ing] the filmmaker to change the camera angle, level, height, or distance during the shot’ (p. 194). There are a number of ways that the camera can be made to move. A camera can be made to tilt to suggest a world out of kilter (tilt shot), or move from side to side from a fixed position (pan shot). Through use of a dolly (a small cart on rails), the camera can be made to track alongside moving objects (dolly shot), or to move through the mise-en-scène independently of the objects in it (the long take).[3] The same effect can be achieved by using a hand-held camera, or mobile cranes (crane shot – see Power Point Presentation – Rear Window taking a crane shot).

    We have suggested earlier that mobile framing produces the sensation of being immersed in the scene (the immersive effect), as opposed to being a spectator outside it. The use of the long take in films ‘represent[s] a powerful creative resource’ (Bordwell, Thompson and Smith, p. 210), and is used by Hitchcock and many other directors to produce immersive effects that enhance the sense of revelation, mystery, terror, anticipation and subjective viewpoints.

    Exercise

    Re-view the opening sequence of Rear Window. Pay attention to the movement of the camera (long take). What effects do you think it produces? Whose view do we see?

    4.10 Case Study: Hitchcock’s style

    You will have noted that Rear Window is the second film directed by Alfred Hitchcock considered so far in this course (the first is Shadow of a Doubt in Week 1). Next week we will be looking at two more of Hitchcock’s films (Psycho, The Birds). The reason we have included these films is to give you an opportunity to consider the style of a particular film director by close examination of a range of his films. Please note that this section applies to the films examined in Week 5 as well.

    A director’s style is the particular imprint that the director makes on his or her films through personal control of the film-making process. In this section we will consider a number of aspects of Hitchcock’s style in terms of the look of his films – their visual presentation to the viewer. Hitchcock understood film as film, rather than as a theatrical staging of events.[4]

    Hitchcock is known for the control he exercises over the making of his films (Giannetti, p. 36). Film scholar David Sterritt has made the following statement about Hitchcock’s control over the film making process:

    Every narrative film maker sets characters in motion, of course, and thenceforth controls (actively or passively) their every move. Hitchcock stands out by virtue of the ingenuity and thoroughness with which he accomplishes this – through his inventiveness in devising narratives and characterizations and through the meticulousness of his preproduction, shooting, and editing strategies. (Sterritt, p. 9)

    So, one of the defining features of Hitchcock’s style is his control over the film making process and the meticulous crafting of images within the story world projected by the film. This can be seen in small details such as the graphic match sequence we will be examining in The Birds in Week 5.

    Here is a further quote from Sterritt with respect to what he calls the ‘directorial gaze’:

    What distinguishes Hitchcock’s relationship with his characters is not only the importance he attaches to having them under his highly judgmental gaze, but also his willingness to allow them an intuitive knowledge that some kind of presence is overseeing their words and deeds. In a number of films, a moment arises when a character’s behaviour seems to reflect awareness (perhaps prompted by a strategically placed on-screen element) of the filmmaker’s gaze; of its morbid, yet clinically detached fascination; and of the manipulations in which the filmmaker is engaged. (Sterritt, p. 10)

    Sterritt’s example of the way Hitchcock has one of his characters embody the directorial gaze is in Shadow of a Doubt, when little Charlie ‘looks at Uncle Charlie on the stairs of the family house, and the latter is frozen in his tracks … by an overwhelming sense of something as close to guilt, or to the fear growing out of guilt, as he is capable of feeling’ (p. 10). If you recall we have already discussed this scene in Week 1 and noted how the camera zooms in on the ring on little Charlie’s finger.

    Question

    Consider Sterritt’s comments here in relation to Rear Window. Do you see an equivalent instance of the directorial gaze?

    In a revealing interview with the French film maker and critic François Truffaut, Hitchcock has said that the making of Rear Window provided him with ‘an opportunity to make a purely cinematic film’ (p. 214). By this he meant that the position of the main character Jeff was equivalent to the individual audience member (the spectator) in a darkened cinema. Jeff’s watching of the activities of his neighbours from the privacy of his apartment enacts the voyeurism of the cinema audience in gaining pleasure from their separation from the events witnessed on the screen.

    One of the interesting points to raise here is that the voyeur is specifically male. One of the obsessions of Hitchcock’s films is the position of the male voyeur with respect to the ‘object of desire’ – often a beautiful blonde woman – and the controlling gaze that subjects the female to the directorial gaze of the camera (e.g. Vertigo, Psycho, Marnie):

    Many of Hitchcock’s films … introduce central female characters who are in various ways out of the control of men and guilty of dangerous or criminal behaviour. In the course of the films they are punished and brought under control. (Lehman and Luhr, p. 86) [5]

    Hitchcock’s directorial gaze – the basis of his style – is directly related to the concern of many of his films – the exploration of desire as a dangerous and unsettling force that disrupts the normal world of everyday life. In Rear Window we see this happening with Jeff’s sudden realisation that he may have witnessed a murder. Hitchcock shows us how Jeff’s voyeuristic gaze is interrupted by the ‘gazing back’ of Thorwald, breaking the protective barrier of the imaginary screen that separates Jeff from the world on which he spies, and exposing him to Thorwald’s retribution, a situation that cannot actually happen to the audience in the theatre, but which is nevertheless enacted on the screen.

    Sterritt also raises the issue of Hitchcock’s manipulation of the cinematic world:

    In some cases, an on-screen character may respond directly to Hitchcock’s unseen yet evident manipulation of the cinematic world. At a key moment in Vertigo for instance, a [horse] stable visited earlier in the narrative by Scottie and Judy/Madeleine swings into view behind them as they exchange a particularly significant kiss. Scottie momentarily stops kissing and takes on a perplexed expression, as if he were aware of the cinematic event taking place behind him even thought he isn’t looking at it. … What’s audacious here is less the event itself – although it is a stunning coup de cinéma – than the boldness of allowing Scottie a response that visibly acknowledges the filmmaker’s active control over the moment, and hence stretches the concept of classical Hollywood narrative to (and probably beyond) its breaking point. (p. 11)

    (for a screen shot of the scene described and further commentary, go to the Power Point presentation). Hitchcock’s directorial gaze is the way the camera ‘looks’ at things: its intrusion into the mise-en-scène and its audacious movements that often violate verisimilitude and plausibility. This gaze is sharp and meticulous; it takes us directly to objects that need to be seen for what they are, and leaves nothing to chance.

    One of the techniques Hitchcock uses to assert his directorial gaze is the long take using a mobile camera. As we have already seen, the opening sequence of Rear Window is one of these long takes, where the camera takes leave of Jeff’s apartment to roam around the mise-en-scène as if suspended in mid-air. At first, we may be tempted to think that this is Jeff’s viewpoint as he looks out of the window. However, when the camera turns back into the apartment we see Jeff asleep on an armchair. The view we see does not belong to any particular character, but to the camera itself. From the opening sequence Hitchcock has managed to assert his control over the film through the camera’s gaze.

    4.11 Conclusion

    This week we have examined a range of terms and concepts related to cinematography, applying them to specific examples in various films. We have also looked at aspects of style in the films of Alfred Hitchcock. Close attention to these applications to specific film sequences will help you develop an analysis for Assessment Item 2 (analytical report) consistent with the requirements of the course.

Examples of this kind of film can be found in German Expressionism, for instance The Hands of Orlac (Weine 1924), or Nosferatu (Murnau 1922). ↑
